This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Court states cases and appearances.  Atty Getsinger acknowledges rec. complaint in 22CF585 and waives reading noting DE hasn't applied for PD yet in 22CF585 but it's likely he will qualify.  Court advises DE re: applying.  Court advises DE of charges/max penalties in 22CF585.  State makes statement re: bond on 22CF585 - requests $750 cash.  Atty Getsinger responds - requests signature bond.  Court orders $150 cash bond.  Parties discuss scheduling as to all 3 criminal cases.  Atty Getsinger believes the cases may be resolved but will defer to the Court noting they are ready to proceed to waiver of prelim in 22CF303 today.  Court notes motion to amend information.  Atty Getsinger requests all 3 cases be reset to the Court's next intake noting she thinks they'll be stipulated.  Court notes if DE waives time limits in 22CF585 she could schedule all matters for PH/WOPH/ARGN at the same time.  Atty Getsinger responds - she's unsure how all the cases will go at this time.  State responds/requests motion be granted to amend as there is no basis for DE to object.  Court responds.  Atty Getsinger responds/agrees w/statement by the State.  Atty Getsinger would agree w/motion to amend in 22CF5 - Court grants that motion.  Court grants request to reset all matters together one more time but after that they will all be set for trial.
